***************************************************************************** 
Treo Talk 
***************************************************************************** 
Welcome to Treo Talk, a special section of the 
Handspring e-newsletter devoted entirely to keeping 
you informed about our brand new product, the 
Treo(TM) communicator. During the next few weeks, 
we'll bring you behind-the-scenes looks at its 
development, stories from the Treo design team, a 
sneak peak at some features and a whole lot more. 
To learn more about Treo communicator, go to: 
http://mojofarm.mediaplex.com/ad/ck/629-4408-2493-28?ck=treo1


----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
The Road to Integration 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
The concept isn't new. If you carry around a mobile 
phone and an organizer, you've probably wished 
someone would figure out how to combine them both 
into one small device. Now imagine if you also had 
to carry around a pager or a messaging device. Do 
this for a while and you'll understand the benefit 
of putting all three into one package. 

But successfully combining these devices involves 
much more than simply fitting them all into a single 
unit. Sure, you might get a good phone, but probably 
at the expense of a decent organizer. That's because 
the individual needs of these devices are in 
constant conflict with each other. A good mobile 
phone needs to be small, but organizers and web 
browsers need to have reasonably-sized screens to 
get the job done. And a numeric keypad is great for 
dialing numbers, but challenging for text entry. 


----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
No Room for Compromise 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
These were some of the challenges the Treo design 
team faced when they started creating this product. 
The team wanted a device that looked and felt 
comfortable as a phone, but also worked perfectly 
as an organizer and wireless data device. 

"Other products that have existed in the past have 
been compromises," explains Jeff Hawkins, co-founder 
of Handspring and inventor of the PalmPilot(R). 
"You've had to trade off some of the main features 
to get the combined device. Our goal with Treo was 
to find a no-compromise solution."


----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
Powerful Possibilities 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
The team began to consider everything that was 
possible in a combined phone and organizer that 
could not be achieved with stand-alone devices. And 
what they found was often times surprisingly 
powerful. The result is a device that actually 
improves upon each of its individual components 
through a variety of unique features.

"The thing about Treo," Hawkins says, "is that it's 
small enough to be a phone, and yet it's improved 
upon the phone and it's improved upon the organizer 
and it's added wireless data capabilities that no 
phone or organizer has ever had. And by combining 
them all together, you basically have a smaller 
product that does more than either one does 
separately." 

In the weeks to come, we'll show you some of the 
unique features that resulted from this successful 
integration, along with the thinking that went into 
them. You'll get an in-depth look at what happens 
when you take a phone, an organizer and a 
messenger--add wireless Internet capabilities--and 
successfully combine them into one powerful device 
that does it all. 

----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
